  "prompt": "Are there legal obligations for financial institutions regarding money laundering?",
  "response": "Yes, financial institutions have significant legal obligations to prevent money laundering. These typically include:\n\n1. Customer Due Diligence (CDD)\n- Verifying customer identities\n- Conducting background checks\n- Monitoring suspicious transactions\n\n2. Reporting Requirements\n- Filing Suspicious Activity Reports (SARs)\n- Reporting cash transactions over certain thresholds\n- Maintaining transaction records\n\n3. Anti-Money Laundering (AML) Compliance Programs\n- Implementing internal policies\n- Training employees\n- Establishing monitoring systems\n\n4. Know Your Customer (KYC) Regulations\n- Collecting customer information\n- Assessing risk profiles\n- Ongoing customer validation\n\n5. International Compliance\n- Following global standards like FATF recommendations\n- Cooperating with international law enforcement\n\nThese obligations are typically enforced through laws like the Bank Secrecy Act in the US and similar regulations internationally. Non-compliance can result in significant legal penalties, fines, and potential criminal charges.\n\nFinancial institutions must proactively prevent, detect, and report potential money laundering activities to regulatory authorities.",
